# TypeScript Domain Patterns

## No primitive obsession

Don't use raw strings to represent meaningful domain concepts. Wrap them in value objects.

**Bad:**
```ts
const userId = `${encryptedIdentifier} ${partition}`;
const [enc, part] = userId.split(' ');
```

**Good:**
```ts
class ConsentUserId {
  constructor(
    readonly encryptedIdentifier: string,
    readonly partition: string,
  ) {}
  toString() { return `${this.encryptedIdentifier} ${this.partition}`; }
  static parse(raw: string): ConsentUserId { /* one place */ }
}
```

## No manual key construction

Don't concatenate strings to build storage keys inline. Use a builder.

**Bad:**
```ts
'category#type': `${PreferenceStoreCategoryType.Purpose}#${purpose}`
```

**Good:**
```ts
PurposeRecordBuilder.buildCategoryType(purpose)
```

## No `as Type` assertions on uncertain data

Don't cast to narrow a type you haven't actually verified. Use type guards or proper narrowing.

**Bad:**
```ts
const consent = record.consent as boolean;
```

**Good:**
```ts
if (typeof record.consent !== 'boolean') throw new Error('...');
const consent = record.consent;
```

## Storage shapes ≠ domain types

A DynamoDB codec (io-ts, zod) validates structure at the edge. It is not a domain model. Don't pass raw DynamoDB documents through business logic — map to domain types at the repository boundary.

## Prefer explicit unions over boolean flags

```ts
// Bad
isUnique: boolean

// Good
type IdentifierScope = 'unique' | 'shared';
scope: IdentifierScope
```
